.TH "TEMPORAL.INSTANT.FROMEPOCHMILLISECONDS" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds \-
Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds()\f[B]\f[R] static
method creates a new \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] object from the number
of milliseconds since the Unix epoch (midnight at the beginning of
January 1, 1970, UTC).
.PP
To convert a \f[CR]Date\f[R] object to a \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R]
object, use \f[CR]Date.prototype.toTemporalInstant()\f[R] instead.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(epochMilliseconds)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]epochMilliseconds\f[R]
A number representing the number of milliseconds since the Unix epoch.
Internally, it is converted to a BigInt and multiplied by \f[CR]1e6\f[R]
to get the number of nanoseconds.
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.Instant\f[R] object representing the instant in
time specified by \f[CR]epochMilliseconds\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown in one of the following cases:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]epochMilliseconds\f[R] cannot be converted to a BigInt (e.g., not
an integer).
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]epochMilliseconds\f[R] is not in the representable range, which is
±10\(ha8 days, or about ±273,972.6 years, from the Unix epoch.
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds()
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] instant = Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(0);
console.log(instant.toString()); \f[I]// 1970\-01\-01T00:00:00Z\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] vostok1Liftoff = Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(\-275248380000);
console.log(vostok1Liftoff.toString()); \f[I]// 1961\-04\-12T06:07:00Z\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] sts1Liftoff = Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(355924804000);
console.log(sts1Liftoff.toString()); \f[I]// 1981\-04\-12T12:00:04Z\f[R]
.EE
